<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="249" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1436,152,251]" pageId="48" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[205,328,188,215]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="249">Etymology</emphasis>
: The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Grey &amp; Smith" authorityYear="2020" box="[567,653,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Hypogena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="reburra">
<emphasis box="[567,653,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="249">reburra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a Latin root meaning “one with bristling hair.” This is a reference to the long erect hairs that cover the body of this species. It is feminine.
</paragraph>
